      <h1>Cannabis Taxation & 280E</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Understanding cannabis business taxation in Maine</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Overview</h2>
      <p>Cannabis businesses face unique tax challenges due to federal prohibition. IRC Section <a href="https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rr-09-14.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">280E</a>—enacted under <strong>26 U.S.C. §280E</strong>—prohibits cannabis businesses from taking normal business deductions, resulting in significantly higher effective tax rates. Understanding these requirements is critical for <a href="/roi-calculator/">financial planning</a> and long-term viability.</p>
      <p>While this creates significant challenges, it's not a death sentence for your business. With proper planning, structured operations, and a solid accounting team, you can minimize your tax burden while staying fully compliant.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="Navigating the Complexity" type="tip">
      While the tax landscape for cannabis might seem daunting, mastering it is a powerful way to professionalize your business. With the right strategies and a solid accounting partner, you can turn these challenges into a competitive advantage by operating a lean, efficient, and highly compliant dispensary.
    </Callout>

    <section>
      <h2>Section <a href="/glossary/#280e-(internal-revenue-code)">280E</a> Explained</h2>
      <p>Section <a href="https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rr-09-14.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">280E</a> was originally enacted to prevent drug traffickers from deducting business expenses. Because cannabis remains illegal at the federal level, cannabis businesses—even those fully compliant with state law—are subject to this provision.</p>
      
      <h3>What 280E Actually Means for Your Business:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>You cannot deduct ordinary business expenses</strong>—no rent, no utilities, no marketing, no salaries (beyond what counts as COGS)</li>
        <li><strong>Only Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) is deductible</strong>—this is your lifeline</li>
        <li><strong>Effective tax rate can be 70-90%+ of profits</strong>—this sounds extreme, but properly structured businesses can often achieve 40-60% effective rates</li>
        <li><strong>Applies to ALL cannabis businesses</strong>—cultivation, manufacturing, retail, regardless of state legality</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Hidden Challenge: The "All-or-Nothing" Trap</h3>
      <p>Here's what many new operators don't realize: 280E applies to your ENTIRE business if ANY part of it touches cannabis. If you have a separate "legitimate" business (say, a coffee shop) that's owned by the same entity as your dispensary, the IRS may argue that 280E applies to both. <strong>Solution: Separate legal entities for separate businesses.</strong></p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Cost of Goods Sold (COGS): Your Best Defense</h2>
      <p>While 280E blocks most deductions, it allows for the deduction of <strong>Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)</strong>. This includes the direct costs of producing your inventory. In a retail setting, this is primarily what you paid for the cannabis on your shelves. However, for vertically integrated operations (cultivation and manufacturing), more expenses like labor and certain utilities can often be rolled into COGS.</p>
      
      <h3>Expert Scenario: The Vertical Integration Advantage</h3>
      <p>Imagine you only operate a retail store. You buy flower for $1,500/lb and sell it for $3,000/lb. You pay tax on that $1,500 difference. But if you also own the cultivation facility, you can often allocate more of your total labor and power costs to the "production" side, which becomes part of your retail COGS, effectively lowering your final tax bill. This is why many large Maine brands choose to be vertically integrated.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Maine State Taxes: A Different Story</h2>
      <p>It's important to distinguish between federal and state taxes. Unlike the IRS, the state of Maine allows cannabis businesses to deduct standard business expenses on their state returns. This provides a vital "breathing room" for operators.</p>
      
      <h3>State Tax Overview:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sales Tax:</strong> 10% on all adult-use cannabis sales.</li>
        <li><strong>Excise Tax:</strong> Based on weight (e.g., $335 per pound of flower).</li>
        <li><strong>Income Tax:</strong> Maine's standard corporate income tax applies, with normal deductions allowed.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Strategies for 280E Mitigation</h2>
      <p>Success in this industry requires playing "Financial Defense." Here are the strategies being used by Maine's most profitable dispensaries:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Meticulous Record Keeping:</strong> The burden of proof is on you. Use high-fidelity <a href="/guides/maine-dispensary-pos/">POS systems</a> that track every gram and every dollar.</li>
        <li><strong>Entity Structuring:</strong> Consider separating your "Management Company" from your "Licensed Entity" to isolate non-cannabis expenses.</li>
        <li><strong>COGS Maximization:</strong> Work with an accountant to legally and aggressively attribute all possible costs to inventory production and management.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <h3>Can I deduct the salary of my General Manager?</h3>
        <p>Generally, no. Under 280E, administrative salaries are considered non-deductible. However, the portion of their time spent directly managing inventory (intake, auditing) may be eligible for COGS allocation.</p>

        <h3>Do 280E rules apply to Medical Caregivers?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Any business trafficking in a Schedule I or II substance is subject to 280E, regardless of whether it is an Adult-Use store or a small medical caregiver operation.</p>

        <h3>What happens if I get audited?</h3>
        <p>IRS audits in the cannabis industry are rigorous. They will look for your <strong>Metrc</strong> data to see if your physical inventory matches your financial reporting. Discrepancies here are a major red flag.</p>

        <h3>Is rescheduling to Schedule III going to fix this?</h3>
        <p>Yes! If cannabis is moved to Schedule III, 280E will no longer apply. This would instantly increase the net profit of most Maine dispensaries by 30-50%. However, until the law is officially implemented, you must continue to file under 280E rules.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

